Definition 2.5. Let $(M,\varphi_{M},\varrho_{M})$ and $(N,\varphi_{N},\varrho_{N})$ be in the class ${}_{D}^{D}\mathcal{YD}$ with associated weak operators $(r_{M},r_{M}^{\prime},s_{M},s_{M}^{\prime})$ and $(r_{N},r_{N}^{\prime},s_{N},s_{N}^{\prime})$ respectively. It is said that a morphism $f:M\rightarrow N$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a morphism of left-left Yetter-Drinfeld modules if: (i) $f$ is a left (co)module morphism. (ii) $r_{N}\circ(f\otimes D)=(D\otimes f)\circ r_{M},\qquad$ $s_{N}\circ(D\otimes f)=(f\otimes D)\circ s_{M}.$
Definition 3.7. A right-right weak entwining structure is a triple $(A,C,\Psi_{RR})$ where $A$ is an algebra, $C$ a coalgebra and $\Psi_{RR}:C\otimes A\rightarrow A\otimes C$ is a morphism that satisfies: $(\mu_{A}\otimes C)\circ(A\otimes\Psi_{RR})\circ(\Psi_{RR}\otimes A)=\Psi_{RR}% \circ(C\otimes\mu_{A}),$ $\Psi_{RR}\circ(C\otimes\eta_{A})=(e_{RR}\otimes C)\circ\delta_{C},$ $(A\otimes\delta_{C})\circ\Psi_{RR}=(\Psi_{RR}\otimes C)\circ(C\otimes\Psi_{RR}% )\circ(\delta_{C}\otimes A),$ $(A\otimes\varepsilon_{C})\circ\Psi_{RR}=\mu_{A}\circ(e_{RR}\otimes A).$ with $e_{RR}=(A\otimes\varepsilon_{C})\circ\Psi_{RR}\circ(C\otimes\eta_{A}).$ Similarly we can define a left-left weak entwining structure $(A,C,\Psi_{LL})$ for an algebra $A,$ a coalgebra $C$ and a morphism $\Psi_{LL}:A\otimes C\rightarrow C\otimes A$ that verifies similar equalities to the previous ones with $e_{LL}=(\varepsilon_{C}\otimes A)\circ\Psi_{LL}\circ(\eta_{A}\otimes C).$
Definition 1.2. Let $D$ be in ${\mathcal{C}}$ and let $t_{D,D}:D\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes D$ be a morphism in ${\mathcal{C}}$. We will say that $t_{D,D}$ satisfies the Yang-Baxter equation if $(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)=(D\otimes t_{% D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D}).$
Definition 2.2. Let $D$ be a WBHA, $M$ an object of $\mathcal{C}$ and $(r_{M},r_{M}^{\prime},s_{M},s_{M}^{\prime})$ an $(M,D)$-WO. (i) If $(M,\varphi_{M})$ is a left $D$-module, the $(M,D)$-WO is said to be compatible with the $D$-module structure provided that it satisfies: (i-1) $r_{M}\circ(\varphi_{M}\otimes D)=(D\otimes\varphi_{M})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M)% \circ(D\otimes r_{M}),$ (i-2) $r_{M}^{\prime}\circ(D\otimes\varphi_{M})=(\varphi_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r% _{M}^{\prime})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes M),$ (i-3) $s_{M}^{\prime}\circ(\varphi_{M}\otimes D)=(D\otimes\varphi_{M})\circ(t^{\prime% }_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime}),$ (i-4) $s_{M}\circ(D\otimes\varphi_{M})=(\varphi_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M})% \circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M).$ (ii) If $(M,\varrho_{M})$ is a left $D$-comodule, the $(M,D)$-WO is said to be compatible with the $D$-comodule structure provided that it satisfies: (ii-1) $(D\otimes\varrho_{M})\circ r_{M}=(t_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(% \varrho_{M}\otimes D),$ (ii-2) $(\varrho_{M}\otimes D)\circ r_{M}^{\prime}=(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime})\circ(t^{% \prime}_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes\varrho_{M}),$ (ii-3) $(D\otimes\varrho_{M})\circ s_{M}^{\prime}=(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D% \otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(\varrho_{M}\otimes D),$ (ii-4) $(\varrho_{M}\otimes D)\circ s_{M}=(D\otimes s_{M})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ% (D\otimes\varrho_{M}).$
Definition 1.5. A weak braided bialgebra (WBB for short) $D$ is an object in ${\mathcal{C}}$ with an algebra structure $(D,\eta_{D},\mu_{D})$ and a coalgebra structure $(D,\varepsilon_{D},\delta_{D})$ such that there exists a weak Yang-Baxter operator $t_{D,D}:D\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes D$ with associated idempotent $\nabla_{D,D}$ satisfying the following conditions: (b1) We have (b1-1) $\mu_{D}\circ\nabla_{D,D}=\mu_{D},$ (b1-2) $\nabla_{D,D}\circ(\mu_{D}\otimes D)=(\mu_{D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes\nabla_{D,% D}),$ (b1-3) $\nabla_{D,D}\circ(D\otimes\mu_{D})=(D\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(\nabla_{D,D}\otimes D).$ (b2) We have (b2-1) $\nabla_{D,D}\circ\delta_{D}=\delta_{D},$ (b2-2) $(\delta_{D}\otimes D)\circ\nabla_{D,D}=(D\otimes\nabla_{D,D})\circ(\delta_{D}% \otimes D),$ (b2-3) $(D\otimes\delta_{D})\circ\nabla_{D,D}=(\nabla_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes% \delta_{D}).$ (b3) The morphisms $\mu_{D}$ and $\delta_{D}$ commute with $t_{D,D}$, i.e., (b3-1) $t_{D,D}\circ(\mu_{D}\otimes D)=(D\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D% \otimes t_{D,D}),$ (b3-2) $t_{D,D}\circ(D\otimes\mu_{D})=(\mu_{D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t% _{D,D}\otimes D),$ (b3-3) $(\delta_{D}\otimes D)\circ t_{D,D}=(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)% \circ(D\otimes\delta_{D}),$ (b3-4) $(D\otimes\delta_{D})\circ t_{D,D}=(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})% \circ(\delta_{D}\otimes D).$ (b4) $\delta_{D}\circ\mu_{D}=(\mu_{D}\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D}\otimes D)% \circ(\delta_{D}\otimes\delta_{D}).$ (b5) $\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D}\circ(\mu_{D}\otimes D)=((\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{% D})\otimes(\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D}))\circ(D\otimes\delta_{D}\otimes D)$ $=((\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D})\otimes(\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D}))\circ(D% \otimes(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\circ\delta_{D})\otimes D).$ (b6) $(\delta_{D}\otimes D)\circ\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D}=(D\otimes\mu_{D}\otimes D)% \circ((\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D})\otimes(\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D}))$ $=(D\otimes(\mu_{D}\circ t^{\prime}_{D,D})\otimes D)\circ((\delta_{D}\circ\eta_% {D})\otimes(\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D})).$ A weak braided bialgebra $D$ is said to be a weak braided Hopf algebra (WBHA for short) if: (b7) There exists a morphism $\lambda_{D}:D\rightarrow D$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ (called the antipode of $D$) satisfying: (b7-1) $id_{D}\wedge\lambda_{D}=((\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D})\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t% _{D,D})\circ((\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D})\otimes D),$ (b7-2) $\lambda_{D}\wedge id_{D}=(D\otimes(\varepsilon_{D}\circ\mu_{D}))\circ(t_{D,D}% \otimes D)\circ(D\otimes(\delta_{D}\circ\eta_{D})),$ (b7-3) $\lambda_{D}\wedge id_{D}\wedge\lambda_{D}=\lambda_{D}.$ Let $D$, $B$ be WBHA. We will say that $f:D\rightarrow B$ is a morphism of WBHA if $f$ is an algebra coalgebra morphism and $t_{B,B}\circ(f\otimes f)=(f\otimes f)\circ t_{D,D}$ and $t_{B,B}^{\prime}\circ(f\otimes f)=(f\otimes f)\circ t^{\prime}_{D,D}$.
Definition 2.6. Let $\Sigma_{\mathrm{pure}}$ be some fixed equational specification (as in Section 1.1 for simplicity it is assumed that $\Sigma_{\mathrm{pure}}$ has no $n$-ary operation with $n>1$). The decorated specification for exceptions $\Sigma_{\mathrm{exc}}$ is made of the equational specification $\Sigma_{\mathrm{pure}}$ where each operation is decorated as pure and each equation as strong (or weak, since both coincide here), a type $\mathbb{0}$ called the empty type and for each $i$ in some set $I$ a type $P_{i}$ (of parameters) in $\Sigma_{\mathrm{pure}}$, a propagator $t_{i}^{{(1)}}:P_{i}\to\mathbb{0}$, a catcher $c_{i}^{{(2)}}:\mathbb{0}\to P_{i}$ and the weak equations: $c_{i}\circ t_{i}\sim\mathit{id}:P_{i}\to P_{i}$ and $c_{i}\circ t_{j}\sim\left[\,\right]\circ t_{j}:P_{j}\to P_{i}\;\mbox{ for % every }j\in I,\;j\neq i$.
Definition 1.5. For each index $i\in I$ and each set $Y$, the throwing or raising function $\mathit{throw}_{Y}\,E_{i}\,$ is the tagging function $t_{i}$ followed by the inclusion of $\mathit{Exc}$ in $Y+\mathit{Exc}$: $\mathit{throw}_{Y}\,E_{i}\,=\mathit{abrupt}_{Y}\circ t_{i}:P_{i}\to Y+\mathit{% Exc}\;.$
Definition 2.2. A decorated initial type for exceptions is a type $\mathbb{0}$ such that for every type $X$ there is a pure expression $\left[\,\right]_{X}:\mathbb{0}\to X$ such that every function from $\mathbb{0}$ to $X$ is weakly equivalent to $\left[\,\right]_{X}$.
Definition 1.7. For each function $f:X\to Y+\mathit{Exc}$, each non-empty list $(i_{1},\dots,i_{n})$ of indices in $I$ and each family of functions $g_{k}:P_{i_{k}}\to Y+\mathit{Exc}$ (for $k\in\{1,\dots,n\}$), the handling function $\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i_% {n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}:X\to Y+\mathit{Exc}$ is defined as follows. Let $h=\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{% i_{n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}$, for short. For each $x\in X$, $\;h(x)\in Y+\mathit{Exc}$ is defined in the following way. First $f(x)$ is computed: let $y=f(x)\in Y+\mathit{Exc}$. (1) If $y$ is not an exception, then it is the required result: if $y\in Y$ then $h(x)=y\in Y\subseteq Y+\mathit{Exc}$. (2) If $y$ is an exception, then: (a) If the type of $y$ is $E_{i}$ for some index $i$ in $(i_{1},\dots,i_{n})$, then $y$ has to be caught according to the first occurrence of the index $i$ in the list: for each $k=1,\dots,n$, – Check whether the exception $y$ has type $E_{i_{k}}$: let $z=c_{i_{k}}(y)\in P_{i_{k}}+\mathit{Exc}$. – If the exception $y$ has type $E_{i_{k}}$ then it is caught: if $z\in P_{i_{k}}$ then $h(x)=g_{k}(z)\in Y+\mathit{Exc}$. (b) If the type of $y$ is $E_{i}$ for some $i\not\in\{i_{1},\dots,i_{n}\}$, then $y$ is propagated: otherwise $h(x)=y\in\mathit{Exc}\subseteq Y+\mathit{Exc}$.
Definition 2.4. For each catcher $k^{(2)}:X\to Y$ there is a propagator $\triangledown k^{(1)}:X\to Y$, unique up to strong equations, such that $\triangledown k^{(1)}\sim k^{(2)}\;.$
Definition 2.8. For each propagator $f^{(1)}:X\to Y$, each non-empty list of indices $(i_{1},\dots,i_{n})$ and each propagators $g_{1}^{(1)}:P_{i_{1}}\to Y,...,g_{n}^{(1)}:P_{i_{n}}\to Y$, the handling propagator $(\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i% _{n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\})^{(1)}:X\to Y$ is defined as follows. (A-B) The propagator $\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i_% {n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}:X\to Y$ is defined from a catcher $H:X\to Y$ by: $(\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i% _{n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\})^{(1)}\;=\;(\triangledown H)^{(1)}:X\to Y$ (1-2) The catcher $H:X\to Y$ is defined from the propagator $f:X\to Y$ and from a catcher $k_{1}=\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i_{n}}\!% \Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}:\mathbb{0}\to Y$ by: $H^{(2)}\;=\;\left[\mathit{id}_{Y}^{(0)}\;|\;k_{1}^{(2)}\right]^{(2)}\circ f^{(% 1)}:X\to Y$ $\xymatrix@C=3pc@R=1pc{&Y\ar[d]_{\mathit{id}}\ar[rrrrd]^{\mathit{id}}&&&&\\ X\ar[r]^{f}&Y\ar[rrrr]^{(}.4){h}&\ar@{}[ul]|(.4){\sim}\ar@{}[dl]|(.4){\equiv}&% &&Y\\ &\mathbb{0}\ar[u]^{\left[\,\right]}\ar[rrrru]_{k_{1}}&&&&\\ }$ (a-b) The catcher $k_{1}:\mathbb{0}\to Y$ is obtained by setting $p=1$ in the family of catchers $k_{p}=\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{p}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{p}|\dots|E_{i_{n}}\!% \Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}:\mathbb{0}\to Y$ (for $p=1,\dots,n$) which are defined recursively by: $k_{p}\;=\;\left[g_{p}\;|\;k_{p+1}\right]\circ c_{i_{p}}\mbox{ for each }p=1,% \dots,n\;\mbox{ and }\;k_{n+1}=\left[\,\right]_{Y}$ $\xymatrix@C=3pc@R=1pc{&P_{i_{p}}\ar[d]_{\mathit{id}}\ar[rrrrd]^{g_{p}}&&&&\\ \mathbb{0}\ar[r]^{(}.4){c_{i_{p}}}&P_{i_{p}}\ar[rrrr]^{(}.4){\left[g_{p}|k_{p+% 1}\right]}&\ar@{}[ul]|(.4){\sim}\ar@{}[dl]|(.4){\equiv}&&&Y\\ &\mathbb{0}\ar[u]^{\left[\,\right]}\ar[rrrru]_{k_{p+1}}&&&&\\ }$
Definition 1.1. Given a set of indices $I$ and a symbol $E_{i}$ for each $i\in I$, the signature for exceptions $\mathrm{Sig}_{\mathrm{exc}}$ is made of $\mathrm{Sig}_{\mathrm{pure}}$ together with a raising operation for each $i$ in $I$ and each type $Y$ in $\mathrm{Sig}_{\mathrm{pure}}$: $\mathit{throw}_{Y}\,E_{i}\,:P_{i}\to Y\;.$ and a handling operation for each $\mathrm{Sig}_{\mathrm{exc}}$-expression $f:X\to Y$, each non-empty list of indices $(i_{1},\dots,i_{n})$ and each $\mathrm{Sig}_{\mathrm{exc}}$-expressions $g_{1}:P_{i_{1}}\to Y$, …, $g_{n}:P_{i_{n}}\to Y$: $\mathit{try}\{f\}\,\mathit{catch}\,\{E_{i_{1}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|E_{i_% {n}}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n}\}:X\to Y\;.$
Definition 2.5. For each propagator $g^{(1)}:X\to Y$ and each catcher $k^{(2)}:\mathbb{0}\to Y$ there is a catcher $\left[g\,|\,k\right]^{(2)}:X\to Y$, unique up to strong equations, such that $\left[g\,|\,k\right]^{(2)}\sim g^{(1)}$ and $\left[g\,|\,k\right]^{(2)}\circ\left[\,\right]_{X}^{(0)}\equiv k^{(2)}\;.$
Definition 1.4. For each index $i\in I$ there is an injective function $t_{i}:P_{i}\to\mathit{Exc}$, called the exception constructor or the tagging function of index $i$, and the tagging functions for distinct indices have disjoint images. The image of $t_{i}$ in $\mathit{Exc}$ is denoted $E_{i}$.
Definition 1.2. For each set $X$, an element of $X+\mathit{Exc}$ is an ordinary value if it is in $\mathit{normal}_{X}(X)$ and an exceptional value if it is in $\mathit{abrupt}_{X}(\mathit{Exc})$. A function $f:X+\mathit{Exc}\to Y+\mathit{Exc}$ is said to raise an exception if there is an element $x\in X$ such that $f(x)\in\mathit{Exc}$; propagate exceptions if $f(\mathit{abrupt}_{X}(e))=\mathit{abrupt}_{Y}(e)$ for every $e\in\mathit{Exc}$; recover from an exception if there is some $e\in\mathit{Exc}$ such that $f(e)\in Y$.
Definition 1.6. For each index $i\in I$ there is a function $c_{i}:\mathit{Exc}\to P_{i}+\mathit{Exc}$, called the exception recovery or the untagging function of index $i$, which satisfies: $\forall a\in P_{i}\;c_{i}(t_{i}(a))=a\mbox{ and }\forall b\in P_{j}\;c_{i}(t_{% j}(b))=t_{j}(b)\mbox{ for each }j\neq i\;.$
Definition 2.7. For each $i$ in $I$ and each type $Y$ in $\Sigma_{\mathrm{pure}}$ the raising propagator $(\mathit{throw}_{Y}\,E_{i}\,)^{(1)}:P_{i}\to Y$ is defined as $\mathit{throw}_{Y}\,E_{i}\,=\left[\,\right]_{Y}\circ t_{i}:P_{i}\to Y\;.$
Definition 2.3. A constitutive coproduct for exceptions is a family of propagators $(q_{i}:X_{i}\to X)_{i}$ such that for every family of propagators $(f_{i}:X_{i}\to Y)_{i}$ there is a catcher $f=\left[f_{i}\right]_{i}:X\to Y$, unique up to strong equations, such that $f\circ q_{i}\sim f_{i}$ for each $i$.
Definition. We call a category $\mathfrak{C}$ a $\lambda$-amalgamation category if (1) all morphisms of $\mathfrak{C}$ are monomorphisms, (2) $\mathfrak{C}$ is $\lambda$-algebroidal, (3) $\mathfrak{C}_{<\lambda}$ has the joint embedding property, (4) $\mathfrak{C}_{<\lambda}$ has the amalgamation property.
Definition ([46, 47]). A relational structure $\mathbf{A}$ is called weakly oligomorphic if for every arity there are just finitely many relations that can be defined by positive existential types.
Definition. A pair of categories $(\mathfrak{A},\widehat{\mathfrak{A}})$ is called a $\lambda$-amalgamation pair if (1) $\mathfrak{A}\leq\widehat{\mathfrak{A}}$ is isomorphism closed, (2) all morphisms of $\mathfrak{A}$ are monomorphisms, (3) $\mathfrak{A}$ is $\lambda$-algebroidal, (4) $\mathfrak{A}_{<\lambda}$ has the free joint embedding property in $\widehat{\mathfrak{A}}$, and (5) $\mathfrak{A}_{<\lambda}$ has the free amalgamation property in $\widehat{\mathfrak{A}}$.
Definition. Let $\mathfrak{A}$,$\mathfrak{B}$,$\mathfrak{C}$ be categories, let $F:\mathfrak{A}\to\mathfrak{C}$, $G:\mathfrak{B}\to\mathfrak{C}$ be functors. The arrow category $(F\downarrow G)$ has as objects triples $(A,f,B)$ where $A\in\mathfrak{A}$, $B\in\mathfrak{B}$, $f:FA\to GB$. The morphisms from $(A,f,B)$ to $(A^{\prime},f^{\prime},B^{\prime})$ are pairs $(a,b)$ and such that $a:A\to A^{\prime}$, $b:B\to B^{\prime}$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\psmatrix FA&GB\\ FA^{\prime}&GB^{\prime}\ncline{->}{1,1}{1,2}^{f}\ncline{->}{2,1}{2,2}^{f^{% \prime}}\ncline{->}{1,1}{2,1}<{Fa}\ncline{->}{1,2}{2,2}<{Gb}$
Definition 1. Let $X$ be a simplicial set. A well-ordered morphism $f\colon Y\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0% pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont% \char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{% \hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox% {\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}% \ignorespaces}}}\>X$ is a pair consisting of a morphism into $X$ (also denoted by $f$) and a function assigning to each simplex $x\in X_{n}$ a well-ordering on the fiber $Y_{x}:=f^{-1}(x)\subseteq Y_{n}$. If $f\colon Y\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0% pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont% \char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{% \hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox% {\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}% \ignorespaces}}}\>X$, $f^{\prime}\colon Y^{\prime}\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0% pt}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt% \raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0% .0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont\char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt% \raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt d% epth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox{\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt dept% h 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces}}}\>X$ are well-ordered morphisms into $X$, an isomorphism of well-ordered morphisms from $f$ to $f^{\prime}$ is an isomorphism $Y\cong Y^{\prime}$ over $X$ preserving the well-orderings on the fibers.
Definition 4. Fix (once and for all) a regular cardinal $\alpha$. Say a map $f\colon Y\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{}\ignorespaces{\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5% pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0% pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont% \char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{% \hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox% {\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}% \ignorespaces}}}\>X$ is $\alpha$-small if each of its fibers $Y_{x}$ has cardinality $<\alpha$.
Definition 10. Let $\mathbf{U}_{\alpha}\subseteq{\mathbf{W}_{\alpha}}$ (respectively, ${\mathrm{U}_{\alpha}}\subseteq{\mathrm{W}_{\alpha}}$) be the subobject consisting of $\alpha$-small well-ordered fibrations1Here and throughout, by “fibration” we always mean “Kan fibration”.; and define $\pi\colon{\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}_{\alpha}}\>\hbox{\raise 0.0pt\hbox{\kern 3.74% 9943pt\hbox{\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{% }\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\vrule width -3.749943pt depth 0.0pt height 0.% 0pt}}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{% \kern 0.0pt\raise-1.999947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt% \raise 0.0pt\hbox{$\scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces% \ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 4.5pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{{}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise-1.9% 99947pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 3.0pt\hbox{\hbox{\kern 0.0pt\raise 0.0pt\hbox{$% \scriptstyle{}$}}}\kern 3.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 11.250057pt\raise 0% .0pt\hbox{h\hbox{\xyatipfont\char 47\xybtipfont\char 47}\hbox{\kern 0.0pt% \raise 0.0ptC}}}}\ignorespaces{\hbox{\kern 3.749943pt\vrule width 7.500114pt d% epth 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}{\hbox{\kern 18.749943pt\vrule width -3.749943pt dept% h 0.0pt height 0.0pt}}\ignorespaces}}}\>{\mathrm{U}_{\alpha}}$ as the pullback: $\xymatrix{{\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}_{\alpha}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}\xy@@ix@{{\hbox{}}}}$
Definition 4.1. A Priestley context consists of a geometric morphism $f:{\cal E}\to{\cal F}$ of localic toposes and two sets of points $X_{\cal E}$ and $X_{\cal F}$ respectively of the topos $\cal E$ and of the topos $\cal F$ such that composition with $f$ induces a bijection $X_{f}:X_{{\cal E}}\to X_{{\cal F}}$ with the property that the diagram $\xymatrix{[X_{\cal E},{\bf Set}]\ar[d]^{u}\ar[rr]^{\chi}&&{\cal E}\ar[d]^{f}\\ \ar[rr]^{\xi}&&{\cal F},}$ where (i) ${X_{\cal E}}_{\leq_{\cal F}}$ is the preorder on ${X_{\cal E}}$ corresponding to the specialization preorder ${X_{\cal F}}_{\leq_{\cal F}}$ on ${X_{\cal E}}$ under the bijection $X_{f}$, (ii) the geometric morphism $\xi$ is given by the composite of the equivalence $[{X_{\cal E}}_{\leq_{\cal F}},{\bf Set}]\to[{X_{\cal F}}_{\leq_{\cal F}},{\bf Set}]$ induced by the isomorphism $X_{f}:{X_{\cal E}}_{\leq_{\cal F}}\simeq{X_{\cal F}}_{\leq_{\cal F}}$ with the canonical morphism $[{X_{\cal F}}_{\leq_{\cal F}},{\bf Set}]\to{\cal F}$, (iii) $\chi:[X_{\cal E},{\bf Set}]\to{\cal E}$ is the geometric morphism corresponding to the set of points $X_{\cal E}$ of the topos $\cal E$ and (iv) $u:[X_{\cal E},{\bf Set}]\to[{X_{\cal E}}_{\leq_{\cal F}},{\bf Set}]$ is the geometric morphism induced by the canonical functor $X_{\cal E}\to{X_{\cal E}}_{\leq_{\cal F}}$, is a pushout in the category $\mathfrak{Loc}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\cal C$ be a structure, $\cal L$ be a category of structures and $\cal M$ be a class of functions from $\cal C$ to structures in $\cal L$. We say that a structure $\cal D$ in $\cal L$, together with a function $i:{\cal C}\to{\cal D}$ in $\cal M$, is the free $({\cal L},{\cal M})$-structure on $\cal C$ if any function $f:{\cal C}\to L$ in $\cal M$ from $\cal C$ to a structure $L$ in $\cal L$ can be uniquely extended via $i$ to an arrow ${\cal D}\to L$ in $\cal L$.
Definition 5.1. Let $\cal C$ and $\cal D$ be preorders. A monotone map $f:{\cal C}\to{\cal D}$ is said to be flat if the following two conditions hold: (i) For any $d\in{\cal D}$ there exists $c\in{\cal C}$ such that $d\leq f(c)$; (ii) For any element $d\in{\cal D}$ and any elements $c,c^{\prime}\in{\cal C}$ such that $d\leq f(c)$ and $d\leq f(c^{\prime})$ there exists $c^{\prime\prime}\in{\cal C}$ such that $c^{\prime\prime}\leq c$, $c^{\prime\prime}\leq c^{\prime}$ and $d\leq f(c^{\prime\prime})$.
Definition 4.2. Let $A$ be a subset of a powerset ${\mathscr{P}}(X)$. The $A$-subbasic topology on $X$ is the topology on $X$ having $A$ as a subbasis. The $A$-patch topology on $X$ is the topology on $X$ having as a sub-basis the set consisting of the elements in $A$ and their complements in ${\mathscr{P}}(X)$.
Definition 1.1. [AT, page 231] A monad $\left(Q,m,u\right)$ with multiplication $m$ and unit $u$ is called idempotent whenever $m$ is an isomorphism. An adjunction $\left(L,R\right)$ is called idempotent whenever the associated monad is idempotent.
Definition 1.7. (See [AHW, Definition 2.1] and [MS, Definitions 2.10 and 2.14]) Fix a $N\in\mathbb{N}$. We say that a functor $R$ has a monadic decomposition of monadic length $N$ whenever there exists a sequence $\left(R_{n}\right)_{n\leq N}$ of functors $R_{n}$ such that 1) $R_{0}=R$; 2) for $0\leq n\leq N$, the functor $R_{n}$ has a left adjoint functor $L_{n}$; 3) for $0\leq n\leq N-1$, the functor $R_{n+1}$ is the comparison functor induced by the adjunction $\left(L_{n},R_{n}\right)$ with respect to its associated monad; 4) $L_{N}$ is full and faithful while $L_{n}$ is not full and faithful for $0\leq n\leq N-1.$ Compare with the construction performed in [Ma, 1.5.5, page 49]. Note that for functor $R:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ having a monadic decomposition of monadic length $N$, we have a diagram $\xymatrix@C=2cm{\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{0}}&\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{% 1}}\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}&\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{2}}\ar[l]_{% \mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}&\cdots\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}\quad\cdots% &\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{N}}\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}\\ \mathcal{B}_{0}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{0}}&\mathcal{B}_{1}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L% _{1}}\ar[l]_{U_{0,1}}&\mathcal{B}_{2}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{2}}\ar[l]_{U_{1,2}% }&\cdots\ar[l]_{U_{2,3}}\quad\cdots&\mathcal{B}_{N}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{N}}% \ar[l]_{U_{N-1,N}}}$ where $\mathcal{B}_{0}=\mathcal{B}$ and, for $1\leq n\leq N,$ • $\mathcal{B}_{n}$ is the category of $\left(R_{n-1}L_{n-1}\right)$-modules ${{}_{R_{n-1}L_{n-1}}\mathcal{B}}_{n-1}$; • $U_{n-1,n}:\mathcal{B}_{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{n-1}$ is the forgetful functor ${{}_{R_{n-1}L_{n-1}}}U$. We will denote by $\eta_{n}:\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{B}_{n}}\rightarrow R_{n}L_{n}$ and $\epsilon_{n}:L_{n}R_{n}\rightarrow\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}$ the unit and counit of the adjunction $\left(L_{n},R_{n}\right)$ respectively for $0\leq n\leq N$. Note that one can introduce the forgetful functor $U_{m,n}:\mathcal{B}_{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{m}$ for all $m\leq n$ with $0\leq m,n\leq N$.
Definition 5.1. (i) A bicharacter, with values in ${\mathbb{C}^{\times}}$, on a finite abelian group $D$ is a bimultiplicative map $\beta\colon D\,{\times}D\,{\to}\,{\mathbb{C}^{\times}}$. A symmetric bicharacter, or symmetric bilinear form, on $D$ is a bicharacter $\beta$ satisfying $\beta(x,y)\,{=}\,\beta(y,x)$ for all $x,y\,{\in}\,D$. (ii) A quadratic form on a finite abelian group $D$ is a function $q\colon D\,{\to}\,{\mathbb{C}^{\times}}$ such that $q(x)\,{=}\,q(x^{-1})$ and such that $\beta(x,y)\,{:=}\,q(x{\cdot}y)/q(x)\,q(y)$ is a symmetric bilinear form. A quadratic group is a finite abelian group endowed with a quadratic form.
Definition 6.1. A 1-morphism $F$ in a bicategory is called biadjoint to a 1-morphism $G$ iff it is both a left and a right adjoint of $G$. Since then $G$ is both left and right adjoint to $F$ as well, such a pair $(F,G)$ of 1-morphisms is called a biadjoint pair. The adjunction $(F,G)$ is then called ambidextrous.
Definition 2.15. [DMNO, Defs. 5.1 & 5.5] (i) Two non-degenerate braided fusion categories ${\mathcal{C}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal{C}}_{2}$ are called Witt equivalent iff there exists a braided equivalence ${\mathcal{C}}_{1}\,{\boxtimes}\,{\mathcal{Z}}({\mathcal{A}}_{1})\,{\simeq}\,\,% {\mathcal{C}}_{2}\,{\boxtimes}\,{\mathcal{Z}}({\mathcal{A}}_{2})$ with suitable fusion categories ${\mathcal{A}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal{A}}_{2}$. (ii) The Witt group $\mathfrak{W}$ is the group of Witt equivalence classes of non-degenerate braided fusion categories.
Definition 5.4. [ENOM, Sect. 2.4] (i) A metric group is a quadratic group $(D;q)$ for which the quadratic form $q$ is non-degenerate. (ii) For $U$ a subgroup of a quadratic group $(D,q)$ with symmetric bilinear form $\beta\colon D\,{\times}\,D\,{\to}\,{\mathbb{C}^{\times}}$, the orthogonal complement $U^{\perp}$ of $U$ is the set of all $d\,{\in}\,D$ such that $\beta(g,u)\,{=}\,1$ for all $u\,{\in}\,U$. If $q$ is non-degenerate, $U^{\perp}$ is isomorphic to $D/U$, so that $|D|\,{=}\,|U|\cdot|U^{\perp}|$. (iii) Let $(D,q)$ be a metric group. A subgroup $U$ of $D$ is said to be isotropic iff $q(u)\,{=}\,1$ for all $u\,{\in}\,U$. (iv) For any isotropic subgroup $U$ of a metric group $(D,q)$ there exists an injection $U\,{\hookrightarrow}\,(D/U)^{*}$, so that $|U|^{2}\,{\leq}\,|D|$. An isotropic subgroup $L$ of $D$ is called Lagrangian iff $|L|^{2}\,{=}\,|D|$.
Definition 6.4. A surface defect $S$ in $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathscr{M}$od is said to be special iff $2\mbox{-}{\mathrm{Hom}}(\mbox{\sl Id}_{S},\mbox{\sl Id}_{S})\,\simeq\,{\mathbb% {C}}\,.$
Definition 2.16. (i) A modular tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is called Witt-trivial iff its class in the Witt group $\mathfrak{W}$ is the neutral element of $\mathfrak{W}$. (ii) A Witt-trivialization of a modular tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a fusion category $\mathcal{A}$ and an equivalence $\alpha:\quad{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{Z}}({\mathcal{A}})$ as ribbon categories.
Definition 2.6 Let $\mathcal{B}$ be a small category. The fundamental groupoid of $\mathcal{B}$ is the category of fractions $Q\mathcal{B}$.
Definition 2.1 The $\mathcal{B}$-free category over $\mathcal{Z}$, denoted $\mathcal{F}_{\mathcal{B}}{\mathcal{Z}}$, is defined as follows. As objects $\left(\mathcal{F}_{\mathcal{B}}{\mathcal{Z}}\right)_{0}=\mathcal{B}_{0}$. A morphism $\delta$ in ${}_{y}\left(\mathcal{F}_{\mathcal{B}}{\mathcal{Z}}\right)_{x}$ is a sequence $(\delta_{n},\ldots,\delta_{1})$, where • Each $\delta_{i}$ is an element of $\mathcal{B}_{1}^{\bullet}$ or ${\mathcal{Z}}$. • The source of $\delta_{1}$ is $x$ and the target of $\delta_{n}$ is $y$. The empty sequence is only allowed in case $x=y$. • For each $i\in\{1,\ldots,n-1\}$ the target of $\delta_{i}$ is the source of $\delta_{i+1}$. • For each $i$, if $\delta_{i}$ is in $\mathcal{B}_{1}^{\bullet}$ then $\delta_{i+1}$ is in ${\mathcal{Z}}$. The composition $(\delta_{n},\ldots,\delta_{1})(\gamma_{m},\ldots,\gamma_{1})$ is given by concatenation unless $\gamma_{m}$ and $\delta_{1}$ are both in $\mathcal{B}_{1}^{\bullet}$. In this case composition is as follows: if $\delta_{1}\gamma_{m}\neq\textnormal{id}$ then the result is $(\delta_{n},\ldots,\delta_{1}\gamma_{m},\ldots,\gamma_{1})$. If $\delta_{1}\gamma_{m}=\textnormal{id}$ then the composition is $(\delta_{n},\ldots,\delta_{2},\gamma_{m-1},\ldots,\gamma_{1})$. In this last case, if $m=n=1$ we obtain the empty sequence.
Definition 2.4 Let $\mathcal{B}$ be a small category and $S$ a subset of $\mathcal{B}_{1}$. Let $S^{\prime}$ be a formal copy of $S$. For each $\beta^{\prime}\in S^{\prime}$, define the source of $\beta^{\prime}$ to be the target of $\beta$ and the target of $\beta^{\prime}$ to be the source of $\beta$. This way we consider $S^{\prime}$ as a directed graph with objects ${\mathcal{B}}_{0}$. The $S$-category of fractions $\mathcal{B}_{S}$ (also denoted ${\mathcal{B}}[S^{-1}])$) is the category $\mathcal{F}_{\mathcal{B}}S^{\prime}/\sim_{S}$, where $\sim_{S}$ is the ideal relation generated by the pairs $(\beta\beta^{\prime},\textnormal{id}_{t(\beta)})$ and $(\beta^{\prime}\beta,\textnormal{id}_{s(\beta)})$ for each $\beta\in S$.
Definition 1.2. Let $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ be a torsion pair in $\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}$. Then $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ is hereditary if $\mathcal{T}$ is closed under submodules, or equivalently by [31, Chapter VI, Proposition 3.2], if $\mathcal{F}$ is closed under taking injective envelopes. The torsion pair is called faithful if $R\in\mathcal{F}$.
Definition 3.4. For any cotilting module $C\in\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}$, the corresponding cotilting class $\mathcal{C}={{}^{\perp}C}$ and $j\geq 1$, we define the class $\mathcal{C}_{(j)}={{}^{\perp}\mho_{j-1}(C)}=\{M\in\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}\mid% \mbox{\rm{Ext}}^{i}_{R}(M,C)=0\textrm{ for all }i\geq j\}.$
Definition 5.14. Let $R$ be a regular local ring of Krull dimension $d$ and $M,N\in\mbox{\rm{mod}--}{R}$ be such that $M\otimes_{R}N$ has finite length. Then the intersection multiplicity of $M$ and $N$ is defined as $\chi(M,N)=\sum_{i=0}^{d}(-1)^{i}\,\mbox{length}\,(\mbox{\rm{Tor}}_{i}^{R}(M,N)).$
Definition 5.3. Let $R$ be Gorenstein and $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}(R)$ of height $\geq 1$. We denote $L(\mathfrak{p})=\mathrm{\rm Tr}({\Omega^{\mathrm{ht}\;{\mathfrak{p}}-1}(R/% \mathfrak{p})}).$
Definition 1.11. Let $R$ be a ring. A module $C$ is cotilting provided that (C1) $C$ has finite injective dimension. (C2) $\mbox{\rm{Ext}}^{i}_{R}(C^{\kappa},C)=0$ for all $i\geq 1$ and all cardinals $\kappa$. (C3) There is an exact sequence $0\to C_{r}\to\dots\to C_{1}\to C_{0}\to W\to 0$ where $W$ is an injective cogenerator of $\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}$ and $C_{0},C_{1},\dots C_{r}\in\mbox{\rm{Prod\,}}C$. The class ${{}^{\perp}C}=\{M\in\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}\mid\mbox{\rm{Ext}}^{i}_{R}(M,C)=0% \textrm{ for all }i\geq 1\}$ is the cotilting class induced by $C$. Again, if the injective dimension of $C$ is at most $n$, we call $C$ and ${{}^{\perp}C}$ an $n$-cotilting module and class, respectively. If $C$ and $C^{\prime}$ are cotilting modules, then $C$ is said to be equivalent to $C^{\prime}$ provided that ${}^{\perp}C={}^{\perp}C^{\prime}$, or equivalently by [18, Remark 8.1.6], $C^{\prime}\in\mbox{\rm{Prod\,}}C$.
Definition 2.12. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian ring. (1) Given an $R$-module $M$, a prime ideal $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}(R)$ is said to be coassociated to $M$ provided that $\mathfrak{p}={\rm Ann}_{R}(M/U)$ for some submodule $U$ of $M$ such that the module $M/U$ is artinian over $R$. We denote by $\mathrm{Coass}\,M$ the set of all prime ideals coassociated to $M$. For $\mathcal{M}\subseteq\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}$, we set $\mathrm{Coass}\,\mathcal{M}=\bigcup_{M\in\mathcal{M}}\mathrm{Coass}\,M$. (2) Given a subset $Y\subseteq\mathrm{Spec}(R)$, an $R$-module $M$ is said to be $Y$-divisible if $\mathfrak{p}M=M$ for all $\mathfrak{p}\in Y$. We denote by ${\mathcal{D}}(Y)$ the class of all $Y$-divisible $R$-modules.
Definition 5.8. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian local ring and $M\in\mbox{\rm{mod}--}{R}$. Then $M$ is Cohen-Macaulay if $M\neq 0$ and $\mathrm{depth}\,{M}=\mathrm{Kdim}\,{M}$, where $\mathrm{depth}\,{M}$ denotes the depth of $M$ and $\mathrm{Kdim}\,{M}$ the Krull dimension of $M$. A Cohen-Macaulay module is called maximal Cohen-Macaulay, if moreover $\mathrm{depth}\,{M}=\mathrm{Kdim}\,{R}$. If $M$ is maximal Cohen-Macaulay, then the Auslander-Buchsbaum formula [17, 9.2.20] implies that either $M$ has infinite projective dimension, or else $M$ is free. If $R$ is a general commutative noetherian ring and $M\in\mbox{\rm{mod}--}{R}$, then $M$ is Cohen-Macaulay if $M_{\mathfrak{m}}$ is a Cohen-Macaulay $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$-module for each maximal ideal $\mathfrak{m}\in\mbox{\rm{Supp}}\,M$. The ring $R$ is called Cohen-Macaulay if it is Cohen-Macaulay as a module over itself.
Definition 2.1. For any subset $X\subseteq\mathrm{Spec}(R)$ we say that $X$ is closed under generalization (under specialization, resp.) if for any $\mathfrak{p}\in X$ and any $\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{Spec}(R)$ we have $\mathfrak{q}\in X$ whenever $\mathfrak{q}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$ ($\mathfrak{q}\supseteq\mathfrak{p}$, resp.). In other words, $X$ is a lower (upper, resp.) set in the poset $(\mathrm{Spec}(R),\subseteq)$.
Definition 3.1. In the following $(Y_{1},\dots,Y_{n})$ will always denote a sequence of subsets of $\mathrm{Spec}(R)$ such that (i) $Y_{i}$ is closed under specialization for all $1\leq i\leq n$; (ii) $Y_{1}\supseteq Y_{2}\supseteq\dots\supseteq Y_{n}$; (iii) $(\mathrm{Ass}\,\mho_{i-1}(R))\cap Y_{i}=\emptyset$ for all $1\leq i\leq n$; and $X_{i}$ will always denote $\mathrm{Spec}(R)\setminus Y_{i}$. For any such $(Y_{1},\dots,Y_{n})$ we define the class of modules $\mathcal{C}_{(Y_{1},\dots,Y_{n})}=\{M\in\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}\mid(\mathrm{Ass}% \,\mho_{i-1}(M))\cap Y_{i}=\emptyset\textrm{ for all }1\leq i\leq n\}$
Definition 1.8. Let $R$ be a ring. A module $T$ is tilting provided that (T1) $T$ has finite projective dimension. (T2) $\mbox{\rm{Ext}}^{i}_{R}(T,T^{(\kappa)})=0$ for all $i\geq 1$ and all cardinals $\kappa$. (T3) There is an exact sequence $0\to R\to T_{0}\to T_{1}\to\dots\to T_{r}\to 0$ where $T_{0},T_{1},\dots,T_{r}\in\mbox{\rm{Add\,}}T$. The class $T^{\perp}=\{M\in\mbox{\rm{Mod}--}{R}\mid\mbox{\rm{Ext}}^{i}_{R}(T,M)=0\textrm{% for each }i\geq 1\}$ is called the tilting class induced by $T$. Given an integer $n\geq 0$, a tilting module as well as its associated class are called $n$-tilting provided the projective dimension of $T$ is at most $n$. We recall that in such a case we can chose the sequence in (T3) so that $r\leq n$ (see [5, Proposition 3.5]). If $T$ and $T^{\prime}$ are tilting modules, then $T$ is said to be equivalent to $T^{\prime}$ provided that $T^{\perp}=(T^{\prime})^{\perp}$, or equivalently by [18, Lemma 5.1.12], $T^{\prime}\in\mbox{\rm{Add\,}}T$.
